# Class 21 — C++ Node with OOP + Timer

## Why OOP (Same Reasons as Python)

- **Official ROS2 recommendation** — all C++ example code uses it
- **Scalable** — publishers, subscribers, timers, services all hook into the class via `this->`
- Becomes a **reusable template** for every future C++ node

---

## Final Code

```cpp
#include "rclcpp/rclcpp.hpp"

class MyNode : public rclcpp::Node {
    public:
        MyNode() : Node("cpp_test") {
            RCLCPP_INFO(this->get_logger(), "Hellow world");

            timer_ = this->create_wall_timer(
                std::chrono::seconds(1),
                std::bind(&MyNode::timerCallback, this)
            );
        }

    private:
        rclcpp::TimerBase::SharedPtr timer_;
        int counter_;

        void timerCallback() {
            RCLCPP_INFO(this->get_logger(), "Hello %d", counter_);
            counter_++;
        }
};

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    rclcpp::init(argc, argv);
    auto node = std::make_shared<MyNode>();
    rclcpp::spin(node);
    rclcpp::shutdown();
    return 0;
}
```

> ⚠️ The log says `"Hellow world"` — a typo in your code. Easy fix: `"Hello world"`. Worth noting because C++ won't catch typos in string literals.

---

## Anatomy

### Class declaration + inheritance

```cpp
class MyNode : public rclcpp::Node {
    // ...
};   // ⚠️ semicolon mandatory after closing brace in C++ class
```

`public rclcpp::Node` → **public inheritance** from the Node class. `MyNode` IS a `Node`, so every ROS2 node functionality is accessible via `this->`.

### Constructor with initializer list

```cpp
MyNode() : Node("cpp_test") {
    // body
}
```

The `: Node("cpp_test")` syntax is C++'s **member initializer list** — it calls the parent constructor with `"cpp_test"` as the node name. This is the C++ equivalent of Python's `super().__init__("cpp_test")`.

### `this->` is optional but recommended

```cpp
this->get_logger()   // explicit — clear it's coming from the Node parent
get_logger()         // also works
```

Used here as a convention to make it visually obvious which methods come from `rclcpp::Node`.

### Simplified main

```cpp
auto node = std::make_shared<MyNode>();   // ← MyNode, not rclcpp::Node
```

Only this line changed: instantiate **your class**, not `rclcpp::Node` directly. The shared pointer pattern stays the same.

