## Timer in C++

C++ timer syntax is more verbose than Python, but the concept is identical: call a function repeatedly while the node spins.

### Declaring the timer as a member

```cpp
private:
    rclcpp::TimerBase::SharedPtr timer_;
```

- `rclcpp::TimerBase` — the timer class
- `::SharedPtr` — a helper alias for `std::shared_ptr<rclcpp::TimerBase>`. Almost every ROS2 class exposes this `SharedPtr` typedef — use it instead of writing `std::shared_ptr<...>` longhand.

### Creating the timer

```cpp
timer_ = this->create_wall_timer(
    std::chrono::seconds(1),                        // period
    std::bind(&MyNode::timerCallback, this)         // callback
);
```

| Argument | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `std::chrono::seconds(1)` | Period — fire every 1 second. Use `milliseconds(100)` for 10 Hz, etc. |
| `std::bind(&MyNode::timerCallback, this)` | Binds the method to **this specific instance** |

### Decoding `std::bind`

```cpp
std::bind(&MyNode::timerCallback, this)
//        ↑                       ↑
//        function reference       instance to bind to
```

- `&MyNode::timerCallback` → **address of** the method (no parentheses → reference, not a call)
- `this` → which object's method to call

> Looks intimidating the first time. In practice it's always the same pattern: `std::bind(&ClassName::methodName, this)`. Once it's muscle memory, you stop thinking about it.

> Python equivalent for comparison:
> ```python
> self.create_timer(1.0, self.timer_callback)
> ```
> C++ needs `std::bind` because methods carry an implicit `this` parameter that has to be bound explicitly.

### Period — note the type

`std::chrono::seconds(1)` is a `std::chrono::duration`, not a plain number. Other useful units from `<chrono>`:

```cpp
std::chrono::milliseconds(100)   // 10 Hz
std::chrono::microseconds(500)
```

`#include <chrono>` is pulled in transitively through `rclcpp.hpp`, so no extra include is needed.

