## C++ Template (Strip the timer/counter if not needed)

```cpp
#include "rclcpp/rclcpp.hpp"

class MyNode : public rclcpp::Node {
    public:
        MyNode() : Node("node_name") {
            // publishers, subscribers, timers, etc. go here
        }

    private:
        // class attributes (with trailing _)
};

int main(int argc, char **argv) {
    rclcpp::init(argc, argv);
    auto node = std::make_shared<MyNode>();
    rclcpp::spin(node);
    rclcpp::shutdown();
    return 0;
}
```

---

## Python vs C++ OOP — Side by Side

| Step | Python | C++ |
|---|---|---|
| Class declaration | `class MyNode(Node):` | `class MyNode : public rclcpp::Node {` |
| Parent constructor | `super().__init__("name")` | `MyNode() : Node("name") { }` |
| Access node methods | `self.get_logger()` | `this->get_logger()` |
| Log with variable | `"Hello " + str(counter_)` | `"Hello %d", counter_` |
| Create timer | `self.create_timer(1.0, self.timer_callback)` | `this->create_wall_timer(std::chrono::seconds(1), std::bind(&MyNode::timerCallback, this))` |
| Timer attribute type | (none — just stored on `self`) | `rclcpp::TimerBase::SharedPtr timer_;` |
| Instantiate in main | `node = MyNode()` | `auto node = std::make_shared<MyNode>();` |

---

## Key Takeaways

1. **Inherit publicly from `rclcpp::Node`** → unlocks all node functionality via `this->`
2. **Initializer list calls the parent constructor**: `MyNode() : Node("name") { ... }`
3. **Always declare timer/pub/sub as `::SharedPtr` member attributes** so they outlive the constructor
4. **`std::bind(&ClassName::method, this)`** — memorize this pattern; you'll use it constantly
5. **Initialize primitive attributes explicitly** — don't rely on default zero-init
6. **`RCLCPP_INFO` uses printf-style** (`%d`, `%f`, `%s`) — different from C++ streams

